01:05.132 --> 01:07.034
[ cheering ]

01:07.036 --> 01:09.303
Get 'im, Jake!
Go on!

01:09.305 --> 01:11.539
Come on, boys,
you can fight.

01:11.541 --> 01:13.007
That's my boy,
Jake.

01:13.009 --> 01:15.576
Let me see
your eyes.

01:15.578 --> 01:17.244
You're fine.
Fight!

01:17.246 --> 01:19.580
Come on, boys.

01:19.582 --> 01:22.583
Come on, Jake!

01:22.585 --> 01:25.353
Break it up!
Fight!

01:25.355 --> 01:26.954
Corky,
let 'em fight!

01:29.791 --> 01:32.159
This game's about money,
about wagers.

01:33.962 --> 01:35.229
Hey!

01:35.231 --> 01:37.832
Back up! Back up!

01:37.834 --> 01:40.134
But for you and me,
boxing's also about

01:40.136 --> 01:41.669
showing people
you ain't no child.

01:41.671 --> 01:44.205
You ain't no boy,
Jasper.

01:44.207 --> 01:46.207
You're Samson.

01:46.209 --> 01:48.209
You're Joshua

01:48.211 --> 01:49.610
at the battle
of Jericho.

01:53.382 --> 01:55.716
I gave you a warning.
You do that again

01:55.718 --> 01:58.285
and the fight's over.

01:58.287 --> 02:01.422
Yes, Jake!
Yes, Jake!

02:01.424 --> 02:02.990
Come on, Jake!

02:04.860 --> 02:06.060
Ooh!

02:08.229 --> 02:09.295
Yeah!

02:09.298 --> 02:12.032
Dang!
Knocked out of time.

02:12.034 --> 02:14.435
Irish Jake
McGinnis!

02:19.074 --> 02:21.575
Future alderman
Jake McGinnis.

02:24.246 --> 02:26.480
Corky! Drink!
Our man won.

02:26.482 --> 02:28.182
Your man, major,
not mine.

02:28.184 --> 02:29.417
[ Scoff ]

02:33.955 --> 02:36.223
Corwyn Roderick.

02:36.225 --> 02:37.925
I thought we
incarcerated you.

02:37.927 --> 02:41.762
My year was up
yesterday.

02:41.764 --> 02:44.031
I've been told you
shot me brother Naomh

02:44.033 --> 02:46.133
whilst he
was unarmed.

02:46.135 --> 02:49.003
Well, you heard
wrong, Corwyn.

02:49.005 --> 02:50.504
Your brother was killed
in the process

02:50.506 --> 02:52.506
of robbing a bank,
gun in hand.

02:52.508 --> 02:56.377
Now's I'm out,

02:56.379 --> 02:59.346
you'd better be
showing me some respect.

02:59.348 --> 03:01.148
Just one of my boys
is bigger

03:01.150 --> 03:04.285
than all of your little
coppers, combined.

03:04.287 --> 03:06.153
You put a hand
on me again,

03:06.155 --> 03:07.688
you'll find yourself
gone to the grass,

03:07.690 --> 03:09.190
just like
your brother.

03:13.462 --> 03:16.530
Corcoran!

03:16.532 --> 03:18.032
I'm going to
police you,

03:18.034 --> 03:20.134
just like
you did Naomh.

03:24.739 --> 03:25.940
Get 'im!

03:32.447 --> 03:34.315
You're dead!

03:34.317 --> 03:37.218
"Elizabeth Haverford
invites you"...

03:37.220 --> 03:38.752
well, that's how
the announcement reads

03:38.754 --> 03:41.522
as of now, but,
ideally, it would read.

03:41.524 --> 03:43.157
"Mrs. Elizabeth
Haverford

03:43.159 --> 03:45.526
"and the esteemed
Norbert Morehouse

03:45.528 --> 03:47.027
"invite you
to join them

03:47.029 --> 03:48.829
"at a gala
in the Morehouse home

03:48.831 --> 03:50.998
"to raise funds for
the continued support

03:51.000 --> 03:52.399
"of our 20th
colored regiment

03:52.401 --> 03:55.202
in the grand army
of the Republic."

03:55.204 --> 03:57.037
"The Morehouse home"?

03:57.039 --> 03:59.907
Why, originally,
I had thought

03:59.909 --> 04:02.243
to host the fundraiser
in my own home, but...

04:02.245 --> 04:03.878
my home.

04:03.880 --> 04:07.681
I imagined that a cohost
such as yourself,

04:07.683 --> 04:10.084
a man of eminent social
standing, might make for

04:10.086 --> 04:13.254
a more successful night
of philanthropy.

04:13.256 --> 04:14.255
[ Laughs ]

04:14.257 --> 04:16.891
And your music room
is larger than mine.

04:16.892 --> 04:19.560
Don't say "esteemed."

04:19.562 --> 04:21.195
Perhaps if it read.

04:21.197 --> 04:23.564
"Mr. Norbert Morehouse and
Mrs. Elizabeth Haverford",

04:23.566 --> 04:25.065
with your name first.

04:25.067 --> 04:26.400
Yes.

04:26.402 --> 04:28.102
Yes, that flows
much better.

04:28.104 --> 04:29.937
So you agree
to open your home

04:29.939 --> 04:31.839
and help me host
the fundraiser?

04:31.841 --> 04:34.241
Of course, my dear,
I fully support coloreds

04:34.243 --> 04:36.010
taking up arms
for the union.

04:36.012 --> 04:38.012
Father, you do realize
this is a fundraiser,

04:38.014 --> 04:40.748
with donations from
you, not to you?

04:40.750 --> 04:41.949
[ Chuckle ]

04:41.951 --> 04:46.453
My son thinks
he knows me.

04:46.455 --> 04:48.355
Have those invitations
printed immediately,

04:48.357 --> 04:50.224
but do not invite
that salamander

04:50.226 --> 04:52.660
William Backhouse
Aster.

04:52.662 --> 04:54.929
Why, Mr. Morehouse,
the invitations

04:54.931 --> 04:56.730
have already been
printed,

04:56.732 --> 04:58.866
with your name first,
of course.

05:01.636 --> 05:03.804
And I'm inviting
all the Asters.

05:06.708 --> 05:08.275
And the winner is:

05:08.277 --> 05:11.111
Elizabeth Haverford,
by a knockout.

05:11.113 --> 05:12.646
Good afternoon,
gentlemen.

05:19.988 --> 05:21.555
[ Spits ]

05:23.091 --> 05:24.692
Fine-looking weapon,
Seamus.

05:31.633 --> 05:33.434
I never seen
one of these.

05:33.436 --> 05:35.502
That's because it's
a confederate gun.

05:35.504 --> 05:37.638
Who'd you steal it
from, you crook?

05:37.640 --> 05:39.373
I found it.

05:39.375 --> 05:41.475
In a union general's
hotel room.

05:41.477 --> 05:43.177
Fair play.

05:43.179 --> 05:45.646
I'll accept
the gun.

05:45.648 --> 05:48.616
Show your hand.

05:48.618 --> 05:50.684
Pair of kings.

05:58.093 --> 05:59.326
Full house,

05:59.328 --> 06:00.628
queens over 4s.

06:00.630 --> 06:02.363
Criminy!

06:02.365 --> 06:04.131
[ O'Brien laughs ]

06:04.133 --> 06:05.532
Well, it serves you
right, for bluffing.

06:05.534 --> 06:07.935
Another hand,
boys?

06:07.937 --> 06:09.470
I'm mucked out.

06:09.472 --> 06:11.739
Well, then, lick your
wounds and scamper home.

06:11.741 --> 06:14.708
Eh, come on, Andrew,
you're my brother.

06:14.710 --> 06:16.243
By marriage.

06:16.245 --> 06:17.678
Lend me a bit
of cash, eh?

06:17.680 --> 06:19.179
Ohh, keep dreaming.

06:19.181 --> 06:21.148
I'm good for it.
I swear.

06:21.150 --> 06:25.586
I happen to have a heap
of money coming my way.

06:25.588 --> 06:27.054
And how would
a shirker like you

06:27.056 --> 06:29.657
be coming into anything
but a heap of shite?!

06:29.659 --> 06:31.158
Har har,
you smart aleck.

06:31.160 --> 06:33.227
I'll have you know

06:33.229 --> 06:34.995
that I am a part
of an enterprise.

06:38.266 --> 06:42.336
I'm regretting
this already.

07:01.256 --> 07:03.157
[ Doorbell rings ]

07:09.297 --> 07:10.831
Good evening,
colonel.

07:10.833 --> 07:12.299
Mrs. Haverford
is expecting you.

07:12.301 --> 07:14.635
Come on in. You
must be exhausted.

07:14.637 --> 07:16.136
[U.S. Southern accent ]
Well, a ride

07:16.138 --> 07:17.604
starting off
from Richmond

07:17.606 --> 07:20.407
sure can leave
a man parched.

07:20.409 --> 07:22.076
Well, let us partake
in some refreshment.

07:22.078 --> 07:23.811
That'd be lovely.

07:25.980 --> 07:29.750
Seamus begs me
to loan him money,

07:29.752 --> 07:31.452
then goes
and cleans me out.

07:31.454 --> 07:34.121
Why do I even bother
with that snake?

07:34.123 --> 07:36.557
Because he's your wife's
brother, and,

07:36.559 --> 07:38.158
if you don't, she'll
hammer your head.

07:38.160 --> 07:40.394
Sybil or no, I'm getting
my goddamn money back,

07:40.396 --> 07:42.229
even if I got to
steal it.

07:42.231 --> 07:43.363
Shh!

07:47.869 --> 07:49.837
[ Snoring ]

07:52.674 --> 07:53.841
[ Snaps fingers ]

08:06.154 --> 08:07.921
What's this?

08:11.593 --> 08:13.160
Tare a'nouns.

08:13.162 --> 08:14.895
What?

08:14.897 --> 08:16.497
Why would Seamus have
an invitation

08:16.499 --> 08:19.233
from Norbert Morehouse
and Elizabeth Haverford

08:19.235 --> 08:21.401
addressed to
Cornelius Vanderbilt?

08:21.403 --> 08:22.936
And why is he
carrying a layout

08:22.938 --> 08:24.872
of the Morehouses'
house?

08:31.246 --> 08:32.780
Criminy, Andrew!

08:32.782 --> 08:33.914
Look, I'm speaking
the truth, all right?

08:33.916 --> 08:35.414
I don't know how

08:35.417 --> 08:37.017
that invitation got
in my overcoat.

08:37.019 --> 08:38.519
Who are you running
with, nowadays?

08:38.520 --> 08:39.687
No one.

08:39.688 --> 08:41.355
You were kicked out of the
Bowery boys, weren't you?

08:41.357 --> 08:42.688
Still got all
my fingers, don't I?

08:42.691 --> 08:44.091
I left them
of my own free will.

08:44.092 --> 08:46.059
[ Scoff ]

08:46.061 --> 08:48.295
[ Sigh ]

08:48.297 --> 08:50.330
Been hearing
the Roderick gang's

08:50.332 --> 08:51.932
taking any idiot
on the block.

08:51.934 --> 08:55.135
Are you one of them
idiots, Seamus?

08:55.137 --> 08:58.372
Thank you.

08:58.374 --> 09:00.808
Ahem.

09:00.810 --> 09:02.509
I thought
this deadbeat

09:02.511 --> 09:03.977
promised your wife
he'd clean up his act.

09:03.979 --> 09:06.079
Seamus did, swore
on the holy Bible

09:06.081 --> 09:07.481
he'd follow the
straight and narrow,

09:07.483 --> 09:09.516
in front of
father Burke, no less.

09:09.518 --> 09:12.619
Sybil will not be happy. She'll
debone him like a mackerel.

09:12.621 --> 09:14.021
Let's go tell her.

09:14.023 --> 09:16.456
You're right. Batten
down the hatches.

09:16.458 --> 09:17.925
A hurricane named
Sybil's a-coming.

09:17.927 --> 09:19.626
No. No no no,
Andrew, don't.

09:19.628 --> 09:22.029
Well, then you'd best
start talking, Seamus.

09:22.031 --> 09:24.932
Okay. Okay.
Criminy.

09:24.934 --> 09:27.267
Corwyn Roderick

09:27.269 --> 09:28.669
got wind of
some hoity-toity

09:28.671 --> 09:30.137
moneyraising party
for negroes.

09:30.139 --> 09:31.805
He's looking
to hit it.

09:31.807 --> 09:33.907
How's he
going to hit it?

09:33.909 --> 09:35.542
I don't know.

09:35.544 --> 09:38.212
Okay. Last summer,
I helped install

09:38.214 --> 09:40.781
some radiators
at Mr. Morehouse's.

09:40.783 --> 09:44.251
I told Roderick that I know
the layout, that's all.

09:47.222 --> 09:48.822
Andrew!

09:48.824 --> 09:51.024
I'd better go warn
Mrs. Haverford.

09:54.729 --> 09:58.665
Hey, remember, Andrew,
we's family.

09:58.667 --> 10:01.368
Let me go and I'll split
my earnings with you.

10:01.370 --> 10:02.769
You're lucky I don't
split your head!

10:02.771 --> 10:04.438
Corky,
watch your step.

10:04.440 --> 10:05.873
Corwyn's still got it
in for you.

10:05.875 --> 10:07.207
Don't worry.

10:07.209 --> 10:09.176
I'll find a way
to reason with him.

10:12.046 --> 10:14.414
Lockwood:
Do animals have souls?

10:14.416 --> 10:17.417
Maguire: Never really
thought about it.

10:17.419 --> 10:19.086
I've known
some men who don't.

10:19.088 --> 10:21.021
[ Chuckle ]

10:21.023 --> 10:22.823
We'd probably be
better off if

10:22.825 --> 10:25.626
the world was nothing
but farm animals.

10:25.628 --> 10:28.061
No squirrels?

10:28.063 --> 10:30.330
Nah, we can do
without them.

10:30.332 --> 10:31.965
Why, do you like
squirrels?

10:31.967 --> 10:33.467
I like
the black ones.

10:33.469 --> 10:35.602
They're always
by their lonesome.

10:35.604 --> 10:39.106
What about...
Rabbits?

10:39.108 --> 10:41.575
Rabbits on farms?

10:41.577 --> 10:44.544
[Laughs]
Giraffes.

10:44.546 --> 10:46.213
Giraffes!

10:46.215 --> 10:47.781
Never really
seen one.

10:47.783 --> 10:49.850
Suppose they
could stick around.

10:49.852 --> 10:53.353
If they stay out
of my way.

10:53.355 --> 10:56.857
What about me?

10:56.859 --> 10:59.426
Mary, I...

10:59.428 --> 11:01.795
I ain't a good man.

11:01.797 --> 11:04.231
Both of us have been
through horrors recently.

11:04.233 --> 11:05.699
What if leaving
five points

11:05.701 --> 11:07.200
is the answer?

11:07.202 --> 11:11.238
And what, live
in central park?

11:11.240 --> 11:13.573
My sister reaped
the benefits

11:13.575 --> 11:15.108
of an evil trade.

11:15.110 --> 11:17.811
She left me a goodly
amount of money.

11:17.813 --> 11:21.515
Let's tour Europe,
just the two of us.

11:21.517 --> 11:25.185
Come away with me,
Francis.

11:25.187 --> 11:26.687
Your Molly's dead.

11:28.690 --> 11:29.923
I'm here.

11:43.838 --> 11:47.841
Elizabeth: Ah, it's
magical, isn't it!?

11:47.843 --> 11:49.543
Magic won't stop
the Roderick gang from

11:49.545 --> 11:51.511
coming in here and holding
up your rich friends.

11:51.513 --> 11:52.646
Oh!

11:52.648 --> 11:54.982
Folks are going to
get killed, Elizabeth.

11:54.984 --> 11:56.516
Mmm!

11:56.518 --> 11:58.251
Kevin, you have got to
try one of these.

11:58.253 --> 11:59.720
No, I don't want...

11:59.722 --> 12:01.121
mmm! Go on.

12:01.123 --> 12:02.389
Mmm.

12:02.391 --> 12:05.559
Nothing good comes
from fear.

12:05.561 --> 12:07.561
Well, nothing good

12:07.563 --> 12:09.463
comes from denial,
either.

12:09.465 --> 12:11.398
Don't be stupid!

12:11.400 --> 12:13.200
I've spent a lifetime
obeying men

12:13.202 --> 12:14.735
who speak to me
in that tone of voice.

12:14.737 --> 12:16.536
I just wouldn't
wager a life

12:16.538 --> 12:18.205
against some
fancy dessert.

12:18.207 --> 12:20.974
But that's just me.

12:20.976 --> 12:22.743
Enjoy your party,
Mrs. Haverford.

12:30.451 --> 12:32.886
Push off!

12:32.888 --> 12:34.121
Good, good.

12:34.123 --> 12:37.124
Lord, I can't relax
with all this racket.

12:37.126 --> 12:39.426
Training's good
for Jasper.

12:39.428 --> 12:42.329
Gives him something
to focus on.

12:42.331 --> 12:44.765
And Marcus, God knows
he's a lost soul.

12:44.767 --> 12:46.266
They're forming
a healthy bond.

12:46.268 --> 12:48.135
Hmm.

12:48.137 --> 12:49.636
Like the bond
of dead soldiers

12:49.638 --> 12:51.972
you saw
on the battlefield

12:51.974 --> 12:54.207
or the bond
of Irish thugs

12:54.209 --> 12:56.843
I saw during
the riots?

12:56.845 --> 12:59.713
Just because we have lived
through violence,

12:59.715 --> 13:01.415
does that mean
that we should learn

13:01.417 --> 13:02.916
the best way
to be violent?

13:19.901 --> 13:21.802
Capt Sullivan.

13:21.804 --> 13:23.270
Well, if I'd known
a fine lady,

13:23.272 --> 13:24.938
such as yourself,
would be in my office,

13:24.940 --> 13:27.741
I'd have foregone
the afternoon cigar.

13:27.743 --> 13:29.242
Do not concern yourself,
capt Sullivan.

13:29.244 --> 13:30.811
I'm quite used
to men blowing smoke.

13:30.813 --> 13:32.813
[ Chuckle ]

13:32.815 --> 13:34.181
As you may be aware,

13:34.183 --> 13:37.150
I am organizing
a gala this Friday.

13:37.152 --> 13:39.920
I have secured
the finest foods,

13:39.922 --> 13:43.123
the oldest wine,
the loveliest flowers,

13:43.125 --> 13:45.792
and a viennese
string quartet.

13:45.794 --> 13:47.294
The one item I have
forgotten to secure

13:47.296 --> 13:48.528
is security.

13:48.530 --> 13:49.796
Mm-hmm.

13:49.798 --> 13:51.264
I've come to find
the men

13:51.266 --> 13:52.799
at capt Sullivan's
6th precinct

13:52.801 --> 13:54.301
are better
at distilling trouble

13:54.303 --> 13:55.669
than any
union troops.

13:55.671 --> 13:57.404
Well, thank you,
ma'am.

13:57.406 --> 13:59.840
That's very nice
of you.

13:59.842 --> 14:01.475
We charge two rates.

14:01.477 --> 14:04.377
But this is
a charity event.

14:04.379 --> 14:06.880
Well, that may be,
but my men aren't big

14:06.882 --> 14:08.915
on giving away
their free time.

14:08.917 --> 14:10.851
Hmm, that is
a shame.

14:10.853 --> 14:13.153
Among those present
will be many

14:13.155 --> 14:15.989
of New York's
leading families.

14:15.991 --> 14:18.258
I have an invitation
here waiting for you.

14:18.260 --> 14:19.759
The mayor will miss

14:19.761 --> 14:21.261
the opportunity
of meeting you.

14:21.263 --> 14:23.563
Did you say
Thursday night?

14:23.565 --> 14:24.998
Friday.

14:25.000 --> 14:26.700
Oh, Friday!

14:26.702 --> 14:30.036
Well, Friday
happens to be

14:30.038 --> 14:31.571
the one night of the week
my men work gratis.

14:31.573 --> 14:33.240
Hmm.

14:33.242 --> 14:34.741
You're
a lucky woman.

14:34.743 --> 14:36.243
All widows are.

14:38.206 --> 14:40.981
Well, I'll see you
at the gala, then.

14:40.983 --> 14:43.683
I've just been measured
for a suit by R.H. Macy.

14:43.685 --> 14:46.419
I think it will fit
the occasion well.

14:48.276 --> 14:50.357
There is
one last item.

14:50.359 --> 14:52.092
I'd very much like
det Corcoran

14:52.094 --> 14:54.394
to be placed
in charge of security.

14:54.396 --> 14:57.097
I'll rest easier,
knowing my guests and I

14:57.099 --> 15:00.901
are placed in his
strong, capable hands.

15:07.361 --> 15:09.328
Why don't we just
arrest the bastards

15:09.330 --> 15:11.697
before the event
even starts?

15:11.699 --> 15:13.166
If there's
a full out siege,

15:13.168 --> 15:14.734
we won't have
enough men.

15:14.736 --> 15:16.702
If we ain't got enough
men to stop a siege,

15:16.704 --> 15:18.604
then how are we going to
have enough men

15:18.606 --> 15:19.839
to make arrests?

15:19.841 --> 15:22.608
The Roderick gang has
twice the numbers as us.

15:22.610 --> 15:25.978
As long as we're dug in,
stick with the plan,

15:25.980 --> 15:27.780
we'll have
the upper hand.

15:27.782 --> 15:29.715
As requested by
Mrs. Haverford,

15:29.717 --> 15:31.417
I'll be in here,
actually watching

15:31.419 --> 15:33.586
the money, but there
ain't much we can do

15:33.588 --> 15:35.188
to lock up this room
without turning

15:35.190 --> 15:38.291
the whole damn house
into a prison.

15:38.293 --> 15:41.461
We're going to need
a man here at the front,

15:41.463 --> 15:44.363
a few patrolling
down the street,

15:44.365 --> 15:45.832
and we'll need
another man

15:45.834 --> 15:48.768
stationed
out the back.

15:48.770 --> 15:51.070
Put it down,
Francis.

15:55.042 --> 15:57.009
And a man up here,

15:57.011 --> 15:58.778
acting
as our eyes.

15:58.780 --> 16:01.948
If we see the
Roderick gang coming

16:01.950 --> 16:03.449
and know where
they're coming from,

16:03.451 --> 16:05.985
we can pick them off, just
like we did with his brother.

16:05.987 --> 16:08.688
And if we make it through, how
are we gonna get the money out?

16:08.690 --> 16:10.656
We race downtown...

16:10.658 --> 16:13.292
mnh! On a cart.

16:13.294 --> 16:16.529
The Morehouses' to the bank
is a good 2 Miles.

16:16.531 --> 16:18.898
Once we reach Chatham, though,
that's O'Connell guard turf.

16:18.900 --> 16:20.566
Damn shame to survive
the Roderick gang,

16:20.568 --> 16:23.436
only to have the O'Connell
boys take us out.

16:23.438 --> 16:25.271
We'll strike
a deal...

16:25.273 --> 16:26.772
grant safe passage.

16:26.774 --> 16:29.208
Francis, I'm going to
need you to speak

16:29.210 --> 16:31.144
with smiling Hugh
O'Connell.

16:31.146 --> 16:32.879
What am I to offer in
return for our own arses?

16:32.881 --> 16:34.747
Big Tim McManus
and little Tim are

16:34.749 --> 16:36.582
in the tombs.
We just let them go.

16:36.584 --> 16:39.719
Just don't tell smiling
Hugh about the money.

16:39.721 --> 16:43.089
Say that Corwyn's looking
to kill me that night.

16:43.091 --> 16:44.757
Which ain't a lie.

16:44.759 --> 16:46.425
So is that

16:46.427 --> 16:48.094
a new hat?

16:48.096 --> 16:49.896
Uh-huh.

16:49.898 --> 16:51.697
Is it a present
or...

16:51.699 --> 16:52.899
A purchase?

16:52.901 --> 16:54.867
Present.

16:54.869 --> 16:56.102
From?

16:59.606 --> 17:03.042
Corky...
Andrew...

17:03.044 --> 17:06.179
I'm engaged.

17:06.181 --> 17:08.714
To miss Mary
Lockwood.

17:08.715 --> 17:10.550
Engaged?

17:10.551 --> 17:12.752
I love her.
She loves me.

17:12.753 --> 17:15.721
And what of Molly?

17:15.723 --> 17:19.058
I loved Molly.
But what am I to do?

17:19.060 --> 17:21.394
Not all of us dwell
on the past.

17:21.396 --> 17:23.963
Is that what
I'm doing?

17:23.964 --> 17:26.065
How many times
have I been out there,

17:26.067 --> 17:28.034
by your side,
searching for Ellen?

17:28.036 --> 17:29.702
Don't say I'm
the one judging.

17:29.704 --> 17:33.139
Francis... Francis,
you're in mourning.

17:33.141 --> 17:35.875
You've wanted to get
married for a long time.

17:35.877 --> 17:38.311
Just make sure
you're getting married

17:38.313 --> 17:39.812
for the right reason.

17:39.814 --> 17:41.981
These vows
are forever.

17:41.983 --> 17:44.483
I know.
And I am.

17:44.485 --> 17:45.952
This is love.

17:45.954 --> 17:47.587
Well,
congratulations.

17:47.589 --> 17:49.622
Francis, you don't
even know what love is.

17:49.624 --> 17:51.123
And hell
if you do!

17:51.125 --> 17:52.992
Your search!
That ain't for love.

17:52.994 --> 17:54.327
It's fear!

17:54.329 --> 17:55.528
It's bullheadedness.

17:55.530 --> 17:57.663
Ellen always said
you were like

17:57.665 --> 18:00.633
a carriage horse
wearing blinders.

18:00.635 --> 18:02.134
When did she
say that?

18:02.136 --> 18:04.770
You were gone
for four years.

18:04.772 --> 18:07.173
You think
she turned mute?

18:07.175 --> 18:09.141
And you... you ain't
got no right,

18:09.143 --> 18:10.643
coming back here,

18:10.645 --> 18:12.745
expecting everything
to be the same.

18:12.747 --> 18:14.480
Go make your life!

18:14.482 --> 18:17.116
Like I'm doing.

18:26.326 --> 18:29.528
Would it help if I say
you're both wrong?

18:29.530 --> 18:30.596
Andrew, you got
to Morehouse's,

18:30.598 --> 18:33.399
2 hours early,
search the hired help.

18:33.401 --> 18:35.134
Make sure none of them
are involved in the heist.

18:35.136 --> 18:39.205
I got to go get fit
for an evening suit.

18:39.207 --> 18:40.673
God forgive my clothes
ain't fancy enough

18:40.675 --> 18:42.174
for this
goddamn ball.

18:44.311 --> 18:46.879
Ah! Just the fellow
I'm looking for.

18:46.881 --> 18:48.781
I'm in no mood,
sergeant.

18:48.783 --> 18:50.883
I understand there's
a... a big do

18:50.885 --> 18:52.518
at the Morehouses'
manse.

18:52.520 --> 18:54.553
I'm joining your
security detail.

18:54.555 --> 18:56.055
I don't need you.

18:56.057 --> 18:59.392
I don't care.
I will be there.

18:59.394 --> 19:01.827
See you Friday,
Boyo.

19:04.197 --> 19:05.698
And right.

19:05.700 --> 19:06.999
Right!

19:07.001 --> 19:09.468
All right,
left hook.

19:09.470 --> 19:10.870
[ Cough ]

19:10.872 --> 19:12.471
Sorry, Mr. Marcus.
Sorry!

19:12.473 --> 19:15.608
Okay.
It's okay.

19:15.610 --> 19:17.643
Come on.

19:17.645 --> 19:19.879
Come out.

19:19.881 --> 19:21.514
[ Cough ]

19:21.516 --> 19:23.416
No, you just keep
working, all right?

19:23.418 --> 19:25.651
Work on that jab, all
right? Keep working.

19:25.653 --> 19:27.253
[ Cough ]

19:32.926 --> 19:34.894
Come on outside.

19:34.896 --> 19:38.397
When Matthew
gets home.

19:38.399 --> 19:41.067
Boy's happy
out there.

19:41.069 --> 19:43.803
Love to show you
what he's got.

19:43.805 --> 19:47.807
Come on out,
sugar.

19:47.809 --> 19:49.942
I've got to start
the cooking.

19:52.279 --> 19:54.380
You know, you're
the spitting image

19:54.382 --> 19:56.182
of my daniela.

19:56.184 --> 19:58.217
Your eyes.

19:58.219 --> 20:01.454
She had
them same eyes.

20:01.456 --> 20:05.691
Soulful.

20:05.693 --> 20:07.893
Ever since I came
here, you've been

20:07.895 --> 20:09.395
turning up
your nose at me.

20:09.397 --> 20:10.896
Mnh-mnh,
only when you reek

20:10.898 --> 20:12.431
of alcohol,
like now.

20:12.433 --> 20:15.434
What is it,
you think you better?

20:15.436 --> 20:17.937
Don't you touch me.

20:17.939 --> 20:20.706
Don't you tell me
what to do.

20:20.708 --> 20:22.475
I'm colored king
Freeman.

20:25.579 --> 20:27.446
Ah!

20:27.448 --> 20:29.081
Aah!

20:31.385 --> 20:33.119
Open this door!

20:33.121 --> 20:35.287
Open this goddamn
door right now!

20:35.289 --> 20:37.022
Or I'll push it
right down!

20:37.024 --> 20:38.491
I got a pistol
in here, Marcus,

20:38.493 --> 20:40.126
and I'm aiming it
right at you.

20:40.128 --> 20:42.128
You go away.

20:45.031 --> 20:47.133
You get back
to work.

20:48.735 --> 20:51.871
Go on!

20:57.377 --> 20:59.345
Miss Freeman?

21:01.681 --> 21:02.648
[ Slam ]

21:04.418 --> 21:07.119
Boy, you want
some, huh?

21:07.121 --> 21:08.721
Boy, I'm going to
teach you

21:08.723 --> 21:11.257
some real shit now.

21:14.995 --> 21:16.896
Want to go back
outside? Just say so.

21:24.738 --> 21:27.139
Come on!

21:27.141 --> 21:30.009
Come on,
goddamn it!

21:31.939 --> 21:33.773
Sgt Byrnes.

21:33.775 --> 21:36.542
I wasn't aware
you'd be joining us.

21:36.544 --> 21:38.511
Well, sir, I realized
how important

21:38.513 --> 21:40.013
this particular
job is.

21:40.015 --> 21:42.115
I thought I should have
my own eyes present.

21:42.117 --> 21:43.616
No drinking, then.

21:43.618 --> 21:45.785
Aye, cap'n. Enjoy
the festivities.

22:19.319 --> 22:21.287
Well, if you ask me,
it takes a real man

22:21.289 --> 22:23.222
to marry
a strong woman.

22:23.224 --> 22:24.290
[ Glass breaks ]

22:24.292 --> 22:25.458
Hey!

22:25.460 --> 22:28.161
There'll be no ruckus
tonight, understood?

22:46.213 --> 22:47.914
Aren't you the
debonair detective.

22:49.616 --> 22:51.084
How is our till?

22:51.086 --> 22:52.485
The money keeps
coming in.

22:52.487 --> 22:54.821
None's come out.
So far.

22:54.823 --> 22:57.924
Are you enjoying
yourself?

22:57.926 --> 22:59.158
[ Laughs ]

22:59.160 --> 23:01.961
Are you?

23:01.963 --> 23:03.629
Rich widows are
in rich demand.

23:03.631 --> 23:06.165
But, no,
not quite yet.

23:06.167 --> 23:07.700
Man: Wonderful party.

23:07.702 --> 23:09.168
Norbert: Yes,
thank you for coming.

23:09.170 --> 23:13.206
Oh, my cohost
arrives.

23:13.208 --> 23:18.578
Try not to miss me
to much.

23:23.550 --> 23:25.351
Aw, look at you!

23:25.353 --> 23:26.552
Very pretty.

23:26.554 --> 23:28.454
Who's prettier,

23:28.456 --> 23:30.857
me or
Mrs. Haverford?

23:30.859 --> 23:32.658
[ Laughs ]

23:32.660 --> 23:34.560
You both look
equally fine.

23:34.562 --> 23:37.363
What about
inside us?

23:37.365 --> 23:39.799
What do you mean?

23:39.801 --> 23:41.834
Which of us is prettier
on the inside?

23:41.836 --> 23:45.138
Oh, Annie,
[Gulp]

23:45.140 --> 23:46.639
Why don't you
go play

23:46.641 --> 23:48.040
with the other
little girls?

23:48.042 --> 23:50.443
There's nobody else
my age to talk to.

23:50.445 --> 23:53.045
Only grown men.

24:22.709 --> 24:24.477
[ Sigh ]

24:28.215 --> 24:30.349
Not a single one
of these highbrows

24:30.351 --> 24:31.951
will talk to me.

24:31.953 --> 24:33.753
Oh, they will hold
a big bash for negroes,

24:33.755 --> 24:36.088
but me? They won't
even say "howdy do?"

24:36.090 --> 24:37.757
At least you got
an invite.

24:37.759 --> 24:40.359
Ha! I didn't.

24:40.361 --> 24:41.828
I bought my way in.

24:41.830 --> 24:43.329
I may be nothing
more than

24:43.331 --> 24:45.264
an immigrant business
owner to them,

24:45.266 --> 24:47.700
but my money's
worth the same.

24:47.702 --> 24:50.136
You bought
your way in?

24:50.138 --> 24:52.438
Sgt Byrnes was
most agreeable.

24:52.440 --> 24:54.507
Useless bastard,
that man.

24:54.509 --> 24:56.042
[ Laughs ]

24:56.044 --> 24:58.110
You look steamy,
Kevin.

24:58.112 --> 25:00.413
Can't wait to pull those
clothes off you later.

25:03.784 --> 25:05.051
[ Morehouse laughs ]

25:05.053 --> 25:06.285
Bonjer.

25:06.287 --> 25:09.255
Bonjour.
Where'd you learn that?

25:09.257 --> 25:12.725
At Contessa Pompadou's
brothel.

25:15.128 --> 25:17.496
Would you like
to ask me to dance?

25:17.498 --> 25:19.165
[ Laughs ]

25:21.301 --> 25:25.104
Miss Reilly,
may I have this dance?

25:25.106 --> 25:28.007
[ Laughs ]

25:43.090 --> 25:47.026
Annie,
what are you doing?

25:47.028 --> 25:48.861
I want to see
if your thing

25:48.863 --> 25:50.563
is standing
at attention.

25:52.566 --> 25:54.433
Child, you don't have to
be that way with me.

25:56.136 --> 25:58.638
Because we're not
at Contessa Pompadou's?

25:58.640 --> 26:00.306
What are you
talking about?

26:00.308 --> 26:02.975
I never saw you
at the bordello.

26:02.977 --> 26:05.444
[Laughs]
You don't remember?

26:12.486 --> 26:13.986
Is that because
you were...

26:13.988 --> 26:17.323
what would Mrs. Haverford
call it?...

26:17.325 --> 26:18.524
intoxicated?

26:18.526 --> 26:21.227
You might not
remember me,

26:21.229 --> 26:22.995
but I remember you.

26:22.997 --> 26:25.831
Your stump?

26:25.833 --> 26:28.334
Annie, don't lie.

26:28.336 --> 26:29.702
Who do you
trust more,

26:29.704 --> 26:32.738
Corky or
Elizabeth Haverford?

26:36.376 --> 26:37.977
Admit you're lying.

26:37.979 --> 26:42.615
I trust Corky, but he
won't listen to me.

26:42.617 --> 26:44.984
He thinks I deserve
a childhood,

26:44.986 --> 26:47.019
but I got no need
for one.

26:47.021 --> 26:48.754
And it's too late,
anyway.

26:48.756 --> 26:50.156
I'm a woman.

26:50.158 --> 26:52.892
He trusts
Mrs. Haverford,

26:52.894 --> 26:55.361
even though she's
no good for him.

26:55.363 --> 26:57.196
Annie, what is
this about?

26:57.198 --> 27:00.800
Mrs. Haverford
had a rendezvous

27:00.802 --> 27:03.102
with a confederate
soldier.

27:13.510 --> 27:14.911
[ Snore ]

27:23.053 --> 27:24.420
Run along.

27:38.569 --> 27:41.704
Turns out the mayor
has the influenza.

27:41.706 --> 27:43.206
I'm going to go watch
the ratfights

27:43.208 --> 27:44.707
over at
Kit Burns's.

27:44.709 --> 27:46.209
Captain,
the Roderick gang

27:46.211 --> 27:47.710
could turn up
at any moment.

27:47.712 --> 27:49.212
Then don't
embarrass me.

27:56.987 --> 27:59.122
Boy,

27:59.124 --> 28:01.257
there's a lot
of money in there.

28:05.462 --> 28:07.830
Samuel!
Is that you?

28:07.832 --> 28:09.298
How fares Harvard?

28:09.300 --> 28:10.800
Top rail,
Mr. Morehouse.

28:10.802 --> 28:11.934
Excellent.

28:11.936 --> 28:13.436
You know,
I do believe

28:13.438 --> 28:14.937
Cynthia was
asking after you.

28:14.939 --> 28:18.307
Oh.

28:18.309 --> 28:19.809
Didn't realize
we were drawing down

28:19.811 --> 28:21.310
on our guests,
Corky.

28:21.312 --> 28:23.012
I thought he was one
of Roderick's gang.

28:23.014 --> 28:25.148
His shoes look like
mine, for Christ's sake.

28:25.150 --> 28:26.716
Just some youthful
rebellion,

28:26.718 --> 28:28.484
privileged boys
dressing and speaking

28:28.486 --> 28:30.253
as though they live
in Five Points.

28:30.255 --> 28:31.988
You should be
flattered.

28:31.990 --> 28:34.123
I think someone
needs to dance.

28:34.125 --> 28:35.958
Yes, he does.

28:35.960 --> 28:37.493
[ Laughs ]

28:50.841 --> 28:52.942
If your bank
will grant me a loan,

28:52.944 --> 28:54.610
Mr. Granger,

28:54.612 --> 28:57.580
I could expand
my business.

28:57.582 --> 28:59.282
I found a lovely
townhouse on 22nd.

28:59.284 --> 29:01.984
Yes, yes, you can apply
in person at my office

29:01.986 --> 29:03.519
during normal
banking hours.

29:03.521 --> 29:05.888
Oh ohh!

29:05.890 --> 29:08.991
I would prefer
to apply now.

29:08.993 --> 29:12.161
The money
would also help

29:12.163 --> 29:13.663
some poor women
from New Orleans

29:13.665 --> 29:15.465
who lost everything
in the war.

29:15.467 --> 29:18.301
This new property would be
such a welcome place

29:18.303 --> 29:20.870
for these lovely young
women to call home,

29:20.872 --> 29:25.141
earn themselves
an income,

29:25.143 --> 29:27.343
some independence.

29:27.345 --> 29:29.846
This is not the
appropriate location

29:29.848 --> 29:31.280
to discuss business.

29:31.282 --> 29:32.448
[ Laughs ]

29:32.450 --> 29:35.184
We are in a mansion with
a labyrinth of chambers.

29:35.186 --> 29:37.687
Surely, there will be
an empty room

29:37.689 --> 29:39.922
where I could show you
the types of services

29:39.924 --> 29:41.457
that could be
procured

29:41.459 --> 29:43.593
if you grant
my loan.

29:43.595 --> 29:46.562
[ Laughs ]

30:09.253 --> 30:11.320
Your dear charge,
Annie,

30:11.322 --> 30:12.955
has warned me that
you're a turncoat,

30:12.957 --> 30:15.858
in collusion with
Southern officers.

30:15.860 --> 30:18.861
Oh, that gir

30:18.863 --> 30:20.396
I sometimes wonder
if children are

30:20.398 --> 30:24.066
the lord's way of giving
women gray hairs.

30:24.068 --> 30:25.368
[ Laughter ]

30:25.370 --> 30:26.869
So I shouldn't report you
straight to Mr. Lincoln?

30:26.871 --> 30:28.371
We're in the middle

30:28.373 --> 30:30.006
of fundraising
season, Robert.

30:30.008 --> 30:32.742
Young widows,
such as myself,

30:32.744 --> 30:34.610
need causes for which
to campaign.

30:34.612 --> 30:38.314
That Southern gentleman
with whom Annie

30:38.316 --> 30:40.716
apparently saw me
is proposing that

30:40.718 --> 30:42.418
we raise funds
for Southern civilians

30:42.420 --> 30:44.687
ravaged by war.

30:44.689 --> 30:46.289
Confederate troops
appropriate

30:46.291 --> 30:47.824
all the medicine
and food

30:47.826 --> 30:49.325
and that which they
don't confiscate,

30:49.327 --> 30:52.028
union soldiers steal.

30:52.030 --> 30:53.963
It's a crisis,

30:53.965 --> 30:56.599
real human need.

30:56.601 --> 30:58.167
One fundraiser

30:58.169 --> 31:01.404
to train
more union troops,

31:01.406 --> 31:03.773
another to aid
the South.

31:03.775 --> 31:06.175
Mrs. Haverford,
I do believe

31:06.177 --> 31:08.110
you're playing
both sides.

31:08.112 --> 31:10.847
Oh, Robert,
in times of war,

31:10.849 --> 31:12.548
only men choose sides.

31:12.550 --> 31:16.886
Women just want
the ugliness to stop.

31:16.888 --> 31:19.322
Byrnes: well,
I spent all me tin

31:19.324 --> 31:21.157
on the Lasses
drinking gin

31:21.159 --> 31:22.658
all across
the Western ocean

31:22.660 --> 31:25.161
I must wander

31:25.163 --> 31:26.329
[ chuckle ]

31:26.331 --> 31:27.730
[ Horse neighs ]

31:31.501 --> 31:33.336
Shit!

31:33.338 --> 31:34.570
Come on!

31:34.572 --> 31:36.606
All right, stop
where you are.

31:36.608 --> 31:38.207
Whoa!

31:38.209 --> 31:40.509
Now! Or I'll blow
your goddamn head off!

31:40.511 --> 31:42.311
Get down here.

31:42.313 --> 31:44.680
All right,
open it up, boys.

31:44.682 --> 31:46.148
It's just spuds,
sergeant.

31:46.150 --> 31:48.551
There's nothing but a lot
of potatoes here, sarge.

31:51.822 --> 31:55.691
Routine search.
Be on your way.

31:58.495 --> 31:59.795
Walk on.

32:05.235 --> 32:06.602
I'm going.

32:06.604 --> 32:09.272
I'll find you in my bed
once you're done here?

32:09.274 --> 32:11.974
Probably laid out
someplace.

32:19.650 --> 32:20.883
Mrs. Haverford.

32:20.885 --> 32:23.686
Miss Heissen, yes?

32:23.688 --> 32:27.723
In the flesh.

32:27.725 --> 32:29.525
Wonderful shindig.

32:34.698 --> 32:37.600
The last song
of the evening.

32:37.602 --> 32:39.735
Not a malfeasant
in sight.

32:39.737 --> 32:41.003
[ Chuckle ]

32:41.005 --> 32:44.774
Will you not
ask me to dance?

32:44.776 --> 32:48.177
My leg's been
bugging me.

32:50.480 --> 32:51.981
A slow song.

33:00.357 --> 33:03.426
This young Romeo
is judge walling.

33:03.428 --> 33:06.262
Your honor, meet
future alderman McGinnis.

33:06.264 --> 33:07.730
How do you do?

33:07.732 --> 33:09.932
What sort of things
do you do, judge?

33:09.934 --> 33:11.434
Pleasure
to meet you.

33:11.436 --> 33:12.935
You know, you're
supposed to look

33:12.937 --> 33:16.138
at your partner
when you dance.

33:16.140 --> 33:17.506
That's better.

33:23.780 --> 33:25.881
You haven't enjoyed any
of tonight, have you?

33:29.386 --> 33:30.853
I've been, uh,

33:30.855 --> 33:33.022
smelling that smell
all night.

33:33.024 --> 33:36.559
You know,
fresh flowers.

33:36.561 --> 33:38.828
We don't get nothing
like that downtown.

33:38.830 --> 33:41.731
Still, five points
has its charms.

33:41.733 --> 33:43.466
Oh, yeah?

33:44.087 --> 33:45.177
Like what?

33:45.302 --> 33:46.802
The kind of man
it breeds.

34:08.701 --> 34:10.168
Robert.

34:10.674 --> 34:12.804
[ Laughter ]

34:12.806 --> 34:14.938
Roderick didn't attack
the Morehouses'.

34:14.940 --> 34:16.541
He must've figured,
if we picked up Seamus,

34:16.543 --> 34:18.309
we'd be expecting
a raid.

34:18.311 --> 34:19.811
Which means they'll
come for us

34:19.813 --> 34:21.312
as we go to deposit
the money.

34:28.053 --> 34:30.355
Ah, shit,
we'll be ducks

34:30.357 --> 34:32.389
in a carnival shooting
gallery. [Smooch]

34:32.391 --> 34:33.558
[ Neigh ]

34:38.563 --> 34:41.632
Whoa, girl,
whoa, whoa.

35:02.354 --> 35:04.389
Sara?

35:23.575 --> 35:26.611
Marcus,
where's Sara?

35:26.613 --> 35:30.281
She hid herself
in there.

35:30.283 --> 35:32.016
Jasper went crazy.

35:34.119 --> 35:36.087
Sara, I'm home.
[Knocks urgently]

35:36.089 --> 35:38.289
Open the door.

35:38.291 --> 35:40.858
Where's Jasper?

35:40.860 --> 35:42.427
Ran off.

35:42.429 --> 35:44.262
I tell you,
he went crazy.

35:44.264 --> 35:47.098
Why did Sara
lock herself away?

35:47.100 --> 35:50.134
I was simply trying
to get her outside.

35:50.136 --> 35:52.103
I didn't mean
no harm.

35:53.939 --> 35:55.473
A person grows crazy,
if they ain't

35:55.475 --> 35:57.642
seen the sun in longer
than six days.

35:57.644 --> 35:59.310
That's science!

35:59.312 --> 36:03.448
Did you touch her,
grab her?

36:03.450 --> 36:05.116
It's not like
I'm a white man.

36:05.118 --> 36:07.719
Get out
of my house!

36:07.721 --> 36:11.889
Oh!

36:11.891 --> 36:13.358
This
ain't right!

36:13.360 --> 36:14.959
Look at me!

36:14.961 --> 36:16.394
You go find Jasper!

36:36.548 --> 36:40.451
Sara, I know you been
through too much.

36:40.453 --> 36:42.387
And you want to shut
the world out.

36:42.389 --> 36:46.391
I understand that,
I do.

36:46.393 --> 36:47.859
But, if you shut
the world out,

36:47.861 --> 36:50.628
I got nowhere to go.

36:50.630 --> 36:53.531
You got to
let me in, Sara.

36:53.533 --> 36:56.367
Please let me in?

36:56.369 --> 36:58.302
[ Unbolts ]

37:30.903 --> 37:32.603
Where'd you g that?

37:32.605 --> 37:36.140
Poker game.

37:36.142 --> 37:37.375
A lemat

37:37.377 --> 37:39.043
from Louisiana.

37:39.045 --> 37:42.914
New gun,
new hat.

37:42.916 --> 37:45.049
New life.

37:45.051 --> 37:46.517
[ Gunshot ]
Jesus Christ!

37:46.519 --> 37:47.752
Up there!

37:47.754 --> 37:49.087
[ Firing ]

37:49.089 --> 37:51.255
Oh!

37:51.257 --> 37:52.423
Hyah!

37:54.560 --> 37:55.593
Ahh!

37:55.595 --> 37:56.828
Hy!

37:58.997 --> 38:01.132
[ Horse neighs ]

38:07.039 --> 38:09.307
Let's get out
of here.

38:12.578 --> 38:13.578
[ Gunshot ]

38:25.224 --> 38:26.624
Whoa!

38:26.626 --> 38:29.227
Whoa-Oa.

38:29.229 --> 38:30.561
We'll take
the money.

38:30.563 --> 38:33.865
We had a deal,
Hugh.

38:33.867 --> 38:37.535
I got a better offer
from Corwyn Roderick.

38:37.537 --> 38:40.805
50/50.

38:40.807 --> 38:43.241
60/40, if I kill you,
too, detective.

38:43.243 --> 38:44.675
But I told him
he's got to

38:44.677 --> 38:46.043
settle
his own scores.

38:46.045 --> 38:49.914
You're safe
on our turf.

38:49.916 --> 38:54.385
Man of my word,
I am.

39:12.771 --> 39:15.439
Where's the money?

39:15.441 --> 39:17.108
We've been
hoodwinked.

39:17.110 --> 39:18.609
You've been
hoodwinked.

39:18.611 --> 39:20.978
And I've been
lied to,

39:20.980 --> 39:23.781
by you,
you bastard!

39:23.783 --> 39:24.949
Argh!

39:26.752 --> 39:27.952
Ahh.

39:27.954 --> 39:29.387
You could've looked
the other way,

39:29.389 --> 39:30.821
just this once, hmm?

39:30.823 --> 39:32.256
I was doing
my job, Sybil.

39:32.258 --> 39:33.691
Seamus was going to
use that money

39:33.693 --> 39:35.126
to buy a bar,
go honest.

39:35.128 --> 39:36.627
Right.
And you, wounded.

39:36.629 --> 39:38.262
Ohh!

39:38.264 --> 39:40.398
Get your feet
off of there!

39:40.400 --> 39:41.899
My shoes are
clean, Sybil.

39:41.901 --> 39:43.401
Like hell they are.

39:52.477 --> 39:54.111
Hey, rich boy!

39:58.517 --> 40:01.352
Thought you might
enjoy some company.

40:01.354 --> 40:04.088
You're alive.

40:04.090 --> 40:05.590
So I guess all went
according to plan.

40:05.592 --> 40:07.925
If we find corwyn
Roderick's body

40:07.927 --> 40:10.828
come morning,
it will have.

40:10.830 --> 40:12.597
The evening
was profitable?

40:12.599 --> 40:17.101
Over $50,000.

40:17.103 --> 40:20.271
[Whistle] Wait.
Where's the money?

40:24.209 --> 40:26.677
Perhaps I'll start
using it as a flask.

40:26.679 --> 40:30.414
[ Laughter ]

40:30.416 --> 40:32.583
I almost shot you.

40:32.585 --> 40:34.285
Yeah, I know.

40:34.287 --> 40:37.121
[ Laughter ]

40:37.123 --> 40:39.557
Let's go make
a bank deposit.

40:39.559 --> 40:41.058
You first, major.

40:57.376 --> 40:58.909
That leg has been
to hell and back.

40:58.911 --> 41:01.312
Thank God for
morphine, then.

41:01.314 --> 41:03.648
Yes, thank God.

41:03.650 --> 41:05.116
You know, you could
get one of these.

41:05.118 --> 41:07.118
[ Laughs ]

41:07.120 --> 41:10.121
Of course, the pain
doesn't go away.

41:10.123 --> 41:13.391
I scheduled
the boxing match

41:13.393 --> 41:17.261
between Irish Jake and
young Jasper Longfield.

41:17.263 --> 41:18.796
I'd like you
to referee.

41:18.798 --> 41:20.731
The Irish and blacks still
curse at each other and,

41:20.733 --> 41:23.100
what, you want to put
on a public spectacle,

41:23.102 --> 41:27.605
Jasper, a colored man,
fighting Irish Jake?

41:27.607 --> 41:29.473
What happens
if the colored wins?

41:29.475 --> 41:31.575
Best case: Irish mob
will kill Jasper.

41:31.577 --> 41:35.379
Worst: You'll have
another full-scale riot.

41:35.381 --> 41:38.416
Barely even a year.
Have you forgotten?

41:38.418 --> 41:39.917
At your side,

41:39.919 --> 41:42.186
I marched up
from gettysburg,

41:42.188 --> 41:43.954
back into my city.

41:43.956 --> 41:47.692
I was ordered to fire
on my own people.

41:47.694 --> 41:49.860
And I did.

41:49.862 --> 41:52.963
There will be
no murder, no riots.

41:52.965 --> 41:54.498
Marcus Freeman
has promised me

41:54.500 --> 41:56.200
that Jasper will take
a high dive.

41:56.202 --> 41:59.503
Well, then, you sure
as hell don't need me.

41:59.505 --> 42:03.774
You think you're the last
honorable man in New York.

42:03.776 --> 42:05.409
But I know you,
Kevin.

42:05.411 --> 42:08.079
I saw you in battle.

42:08.081 --> 42:11.449
I saw you
during the riots.

42:15.020 --> 42:16.687
[ Sigh ]

42:16.689 --> 42:18.923
When I was, uh,

42:18.925 --> 42:23.060
first on morphine
for my leg,

42:23.062 --> 42:30.067
it put me on this
spirit plane.

42:30.069 --> 42:34.205
I saw this beautiful
ghost, but,

42:34.207 --> 42:37.241
she hasn't
come back to me.

42:37.243 --> 42:42.913
They never do.

42:42.915 --> 42:46.550
What happens if...

42:46.552 --> 42:49.553
if I die,

42:49.555 --> 42:53.858
never knowing what
happened to Ellen

42:53.860 --> 42:57.995
or who killed
my little girl?

42:57.997 --> 43:01.832
Then you'll be dead.

43:01.834 --> 43:05.803
Same as all of those
who have gone before you.

43:05.805 --> 43:07.371
Same as all of us
who will follow.

43:09.908 --> 43:14.245
None of it
will matter.

43:14.247 --> 43:16.914
[ Sigh ]

43:16.916 --> 43:18.416
Not a bit.

43:26.629 --> 43:29.641
Sync and correction by GeirDM
www.addic7ed.com

43:30.095 --> 43:32.563
ah! You pulled
the wrong tooth!

43:32.565 --> 43:33.964
What the hell's
the matter with you?!

43:33.966 --> 43:35.933
How many dead bodies we got
laying about this morning?

43:35.935 --> 43:37.735
Only one: A dentist
over on Duane.

43:37.737 --> 43:39.703
I saw the way he
smacked you around.

43:39.705 --> 43:42.039
Annie is a tortured
girl, monsignor.

43:42.041 --> 43:43.340
Aah!

43:43.342 --> 43:45.009
Your husband seemed
to like me just fine.

43:45.011 --> 43:46.377
You can teach me
the things

43:46.379 --> 43:48.078
I need to know,
miss Eva.

43:48.080 --> 43:49.547
What the girl needs
is a mother and love,

43:49.549 --> 43:51.148
not the kind she'll
get from whores.

43:51.150 --> 43:52.950
Ain't no Irishman
who can hurt me.

43:52.952 --> 43:56.215
If he beats McGinnis, you know
these fine people will riot.

43:56.506 --> 43:57.866
Oh, Jesus.

